analytic.title: Superior mechanical properties and strengthening mechanisms of lightweight AlxCrNbVMo refractory high-entropy alloys (x = 0, 0.5, 1.0) fabricated by the powder metallurgy process

biblStruct.note: Received 10 May 2020 Received in revised form 23 June 2020 Accepted 3 July 2020

textClass.keywords: High-entropy alloy Powder metallurgy Refractory Strengthening mechanisms Oxide dispersoids

div.p: Light and strong AlxCrNbVMo (x = 0, 0.5, and 1.0) refractory high-entropy alloys (RHEAs) were designed and fabricated via a the powder metallurgical process. The microstructure of the AlxCrNbVMo alloys consisted of a single BCC crystalline structure with a sub-micron grain size of 2-3 m, and small amounts (< 4 vol.%) of fine oxide dispersoids. This homogeneous microstructure, without chemical segregation or micropores was achieved via high-energy ball milling and spark-plasma sintering. The alloys exhibited superior mechanical properties at 25 and 1000 • C compared to those of other RHEAs. Here, CrNbVMo alloy showed a yield strength of 2743 MPa at room temperature. Surprisingly, the yield strength of the CrNbVMo alloy at 1000 • C was 1513 MPa. The specific yield strength of the CrNbVMo alloy was increased by 27 % and 87 % at 25 and 1000 • C, respectively, compared to the AlMo 0.5 NbTa 0.5 TiZr RHEA, which exhibited so far the highest specific yield strength among the cast RHEAs. The addition of Al to CrNbVMo alloy was advantageous in reducing its reduce density to below 8.0 g/cm 3 , while the elastic modulus decreased due to the much lower elastic modulus of Al compared to that of the CrNbVMo alloy. Quantitative analysis of the strengthening contributions, showed that the solid solution strengthening, arising from a large misfit effect due to the size and modulus, and the high shear modulus of matrix, was revealed to predominant strengthening mechanism, accounting for over 50 % of the yield strength of the AlxCrNbVMo RHEAs.

div.head: Introduction
div.p: As a unique and novel kind of alloy, high-entropy alloys (HEAs) have attracted much attention because of their outstanding mechanical properties, including high strength and moderate toughness [1,2]. Unlike traditional alloys, HEAs have several principal elements [3,4]. As a class of HEAs, the refractory high-entropy alloys (RHEAs) that consist principally of refractory elements (Nb, Ta, and W) exhibit better mechanical properties at elevated temperatures than conventional Ni-based superalloys [5][6][7]. The outstanding strength and heat-softening resistance at a high temperature of RHEAs make them be promising materials for high temperature applications such as advanced gas turbines and airplane engines. To date, several RHEA systems have been reported so far, but they have been developed to a limited extent compared to its possible number of alloy design [8]. It is thus important to design and develop new RHEAs which have moderate ductility at room temperature while maintaining the strength for practical applications. RHEAs exhibit disordered BCC and/or ordered B2 crystalline structure, and may also contain both incoherent and brittle intermetallic phases, mostly the sigma or Laves phases [9,10]. To achieve moderate ductility at room temperature, the formation of such sigma and Laves phases needs to be avoided. Furthermore, the aerospace industry requires alloys with low-density for high temperature load-bearing structure and thermal protection systems [11]. Thus, novel RHEAs are desirable to have lower density than that of the conventional Ni-based superalloys while keeping the superior mechanical properties.

When it comes to the fabrication process for RHEAs, they have typically been fabricated via simple arc-melting and casting, in association with chemical segregation and grain coarsening. By contrast, fabrication using powder metallurgy (PM) affords several advantages including a homogeneous microstructure, fine grain size, and lower processing temperature [7,12,13]. Furthermore, PM procedures are more suitable for the fabrication of small and precise RHEA components. PM-processed RHEAs may be further strengthened by in-situ formation of dispersoids [13][14][15].

In the view of the above findings, we developed novel RHEAs of CrNbVMo (Al 0 ), Al 0.5 CrNbVMo (Al 0.5 ), and Al 1.0 CrNbVMo (Al 1.0 ) using PM procedures. The alloys were synthesized by high-energy ball milling and spark-plasma sintering (SPS). All of the RHEAs were designed to have only a BCC structure without brittle sigma or Laves phases, and are of low density (< 8.0 g/cm 3 ), i.e., lighter than traditional Ni-based superalloys. The microstructure and phase evolution of the alloys were systemically investigated. The mechanical properties of the RHEAs were characterized by compressive tests at 25 and 1000 • C, and compared to those of other RHEAs and the Ni-based superalloys. We also studied the related strengthening mechanisms of the PM-processed Al 0 , Al 0.5 , and Al 1.0 to achieve a comprehensive understanding of their outstanding mechanical properties.

div.head: Materials and methods
div.p: Elemental powders (purity > 99 %) were loaded into SKD-11 vials with tungsten carbide balls and milled in a high-energy planetary mill (Pulverisette 5; Fritsch) at 200 rpm for the optimal time of 12 h under argon (the milling period was optimized in our previous study [16]). A process control agent was not used, so as to ensure the purity of the milled powders. Powder consolidation was achieved by SPS (SPS515S; Fuji Electronic Industrial) at 1200 • C. Crystalline structures were analyzed via high-resolution X-ray diffraction (XRD; SmartLab; Rigaku) using Cu K␣ radiation. Microstructures of the alloys were analyzed by a scanning electron microscope (SEM; SU5000; Hitachi), equipped with an energy-dispersive spectrometer (EDS) and an electron back-scattered diffraction (EBSD) detector; and using a transmission electron microscope (TEM; JEM-ARM200 F; JEOL). SEM samples were prepared by grinding and polishing using diamond paste and colloidal silica. Samples for TEM analysis were fabricated by a focused ion beam (FB-2100; Hitachi). The volume fraction and average radius of the inclusions were measured quantitatively using image analysis software (ImagePartner, Saramsoft Co). The density of sintered specimens was measured using the Archimedes method with distilled water. The elastic moduli of the alloys were evaluated by nanoindentation (iMicro Nanoindenter; Nanomechanics) at room temperature. Each elastic modulus value is an average of 12 indents (4 × 3 matrix) obtained under the same indentation strain rate of 0.005s -1 . Compression tests were performed at 25 and 1000 • C in laboratory air using a universal testing machine (MTS 810, MTS Systems Corp.) under an engineering strain rate of 0.001 s -1 . For compression tests, cylindrical samples (∅ 3 × 4.5 mm) were prepared by electric discharge machining. Strains at room temperature were measured using a customized strain gauge placed beside each sample. When evaluating compression at 1000 • C, crosshead displacement was used to calculate strain.

div.head: Results
div.p: Phase diagrams of the Al 0 , Al 0.5 , and Al 1.0 RHEAs showed the development of single BCC phases. Thermo-Calc 2017b software (TCHEA 3.0) was utilized to obtain the equilibrium phase diagram for the alloys. Fig. 1 shows the equilibrium phase fraction- temperature diagrams for the alloys over a temperature range of 500-2000 • C. For Al 0 alloy (Fig. 1(a)), a single BCC phase was predicted for temperatures above 1268 • C. For the Al 0.5 and Al 1.0 alloys, the formation of brittle intermetallic phases, such as A15 and Laves, was predicted. Usually, Al is added to BCC-based refractory HEAs to reduce the density and increase BCC phase stability [8]. However, the addition of Al to refractory elements (especially Ti, Zr, and Hf) may induce the formation of brittle intermetallic phases (the Laves or B2 phases) because of the large negative enthalpies of their formation [8]. For the Al 0.5 and Al 1.0 alloys (Fig. 1(b-c)), due to the relatively weak interaction between the elements that we used (Cr, Nb, V, and Mo) and Al, the intermetallic phase (i.e., Laves) completely dissolved before nucleation of the liquid phase took place. As a result, single BCC phases can be formed at temperatures > 1145 • C for Al 0.5 , and > 1327 • C for Al 1.0 . Here, the SPS temperature measured using an optical pyrometer was 1200 • C, which was lower than that for the single BCC regions. According to the literature [18], a difference in temperature occurs between the graphite mold and powders therein during SPS. The higher the sintering temperature applied to the mold, the greater the temperature deviation. For ZrN, the temperature difference reached 141 • C at a pyrometer temperature of 1200 • C [18]. Since the ZrN a conducting ceramic having metallic-like electrical and thermal conductivity, similar temperature deviation may occur in the case of the Al 0 , Al 0.5 , and Al 1.0 RHEAs powders. The single BCC phases formed during the SPS were retained at room temperature due to the relatively rapid cooling after SPS [14]. The reason for applying the SPS temperature of 1200 • C, instead of using a sintering temperature of 1341 • C (actual temperature > 1500 • C), was to minimize diffusion of C from the graphite mold or punch during SPS, which could induce the formation of brittle carbides.

Fig. 2 shows the XRD patterns of sintered Al 0 , Al 0.5 , and Al 1.0 . Only the BCC structure was evident for the sintered alloys without any brittle intermetallic phases, as shown in Fig. 2(a). The XRD analysis results are in accordance with the phases predicted based on phase diagram analysis. Extremely weak diffraction patterns were seen for the alloys (Fig. 2(b-d)). For Al 0.5 and Al 1.0 , the minor peaks closely matched those of Al 2 O 3 (PDF# 01-075-0785). Given the strong affinity of oxygen for Al, Al readily absorbs oxygen from residual air in the SPS chamber and thin oxide scale on the surface of the powders, inducing Al 2 O 3 formation during subsequent sintering [16]. The minor Al 0 peaks well matched those of NbO 0.7 (PDF# 00-047-1694). The formation of this Nb-rich oxide in Al 0 is attributable to the higher oxygen affinity of Nb compared to Cr, Mo, and V.

Fig. 3 shows the corresponding SEM-backscattered electron, scanning TEM, and EBSD images of the Al 0 , Al 0.5 , and Al 1.0 , the densities of which were 8.03, 7.53, and 7.05 g/cm 3 , respectively. The relative densities of the sintered alloys were close to 100 %, supported by the absence of micropores. It is apparent that the three alloys were grey in color with uniformly dispersed darker inclusions (marked by white arrows). In Al 0 , the volume fraction of the dark-grey inclusions was 1.71 % (Fig. 3(a)). In Al 0.5 and Al 1.0 , black inclusions with volume fractions of 3.71 % and 3.79 %, respectively, were evident (Fig. 3(b-c)). The chemical compositions of the various phases were analyzed via EDS point analysis, and the results are summarized in Table 1. The grey matrices exhibited compositions close to nominal; the dark-grey inclusion of Al 0 was enriched with Nb and O, and the black inclusions of Al 0. 2.95 m, respectively, i.e., much finer than those of cast HEAs due to the rapidity of SPS and the Zener-pinning effects of the oxide inclusions [19]. The density, grain sizes of BCC matrices, volume fraction, and mean size of the oxide inclusions are listed in Table 2.

Although the XRD results for the Al 0 , Al 0.5 and Al 1.0 represent the formation of the disordered BCC phase, the results are insufficient to determine whether the alloys are ordered or not [20]. According to literature, Al-containing RHEAs are prone to form the ordered B2 phase [20][21][22][23][24]. Thus, the Al 0.5 and Al 1.0 may be composed of the ordered B2 phase. To confirm this issue, TEM investigation on the Al 0 , Al 0.5 , and Al 1.0 is conducted. Fig. 4 presents the TEM bright field (TEM-BF) images and corresponding SAED patterns of the alloys. The TEM-BF images of the alloys (Fig. 4(a)-(c)) confirm the presence of a single BCC phase containing minor oxide inclusions that marked as white arrows. The SAED patterns for the BCC matrices of the alloys show the absence of B2 ordering, indicating that the alloys consist of the disordered BCC phase. The oxide inclusions are confirmed to NbO 0.7 (Al 0 ) and Al 2 O 3 (Al 0.5 and Al 1.0 ) by corresponding SAED and the fast Fourier transform (FFT), which are in accordance with the analysis results of the XRD and SEM/EDS. Fig. 5(a) and (b) show the engineering compressive stress-strain curves of the Al 0 , Al 0.5 , and Al 1.0 RHEAs at 25 and 1000 • C, respectively. The compressive mechanical properties of the alloys are summarized in Table 3. Despite the single phase nature of the alloys, which lacked hard intermetallic phases, they exhibited outstanding yield strength at room and elevated temperatures (> 2300 and 1000 MPa, respectively). The absence of brittle intermetallic phases explained the moderate fracture strains (> 9.9 %), resulting in a good combination of strength and ductility. The elastic modulus values of the alloys, which were measured by the nanoindentation test, were 217, 208, and 200 GPa for Al 0 , Al 0.5 , and Al 1.0 , respectively (Fig. S1). These values were derived at an indentation depth of 750 nm. As the Al content increased, the elastic modulus decreased due to the much lower modulus of Al (70.6 GPa) [25] compared to that of the Al 0 alloy. The yield strength and specific yield strength also decreased, although there was a compensatory increase in fracture strain as the concentration of Al increased. As the most important property for high-temperature structural materials, the specific yield strength of the Al 0 , Al 0.5 and Al 1.0 RHEAs are compared with those of typical BCC RHEAs processed by casting in Fig. 6 [5,11,17,[26][27][28][29][30][31][32][33][34]. The specific yield strength of the AlxCrNbVMo RHEAs was much higher than those of other BCC RHEAs at both 25 and 1000 • C. Surprisingly, the Al 0 alloy showed an ultra-high yield strength of 1513 MPa at 1000 • C. Compared to the AlMo 0.5 NbTa 0.5 TiZr, which exhibited the best specific yield strength among the cast RHEAs [17], the Al 0 exhibited 27 % and 87 % increases at 25 and 1000 • C, respectively.

To confirm phase transitions of the Al 0 , Al 0.5 and Al 1.0 alloys after the compression test at 1000 • C, the microstructure of the deformed samples was analyzed by means of SEM/BSE and STEM. Fig. S2 illustrates the microstructure of the alloys after the deformation at 1000 • C. For Al 0 and Al 0.5 alloys (Fig. S2(a)-(b)), no indication of microstructural change observed compared to the as-sintered specimens. In the case of Al 1.0 , however, phase evolution was The EDS mapping (Fig. 7(c)) on the squared area in Fig. 7(a) showed that the second phase was Cr and Nb rich. The FFT and EDS mapping demonstrate that the second phase is Cr 2 Nb Laves phase. The formation of the Laves phase only at Al 1.0 at 1000 • C is consistent with the predicted result on phase diagrams of the alloys (Fig. 1). Since the evolution of such brittle intermetallic phase at the elevated temperature makes RHEAs difficult to apply to high temperature materials, the phase stability at the high temperature should be considered an important factor in the future development of RHEAs.

div.head: Discussion
div.p: The outstanding mechanical properties of Al 0 , Al 0.5 and Al 1.0 RHEAs are attributed to the combined effect of several strengthening mechanisms: friction stress, solid solution strengthening, grain boundary strengthening, dislocation strengthening, and Orowan strengthening by oxide inclusion. The friction stress is the intrinsic resistance of the lattice to dislocation movement. According to the literature [35], the strengthening effect of the friction stress in BCC RHEAs is indistinguishable from the solid solution strengthening which will be described following section. To combine the contributions of these strengthening mechanisms, a quadratic model has been proposed that considers the superposition of grain boundary, Orowan, and dislocation strengthening when an external force is applied [36][37][38]. Clyne [39] proposed that the strengthening contributions which act more or less uniformly throughout the matrix must be added linearly, whereas strengthening mechanisms which act unevenly throughout the matrix are suitably combined as the root of the sum of the squares. According to literature [40], the strengthening by grain boundary, Orowan and dislocation acts more or less unevenly throughout the matrix compared to the solid solution strengthening for the particle-reinforced metal matrix composites with nano-scale grains. Since the Al 0 , Al 0.5 and Al 1.0 can be considered as oxide-reinforced high-entropy alloy composites having nano-grains, the quadratic model can be applied to predict the yield strength of the alloys. During high-energy ball milling, the RHEA powders are severely deformed, resulting in initial formation of dislocations with a relatively high density.

The powder of Al 0 , having a higher G, deformed less readily than those of Al 0.5 and Al 1.0 , so that more initial dislocations may have accumulated in the Al 0 powders under the same ball-milling conditions. Because of the extremely rapid heating and short dwell time of SPS, insufficient annihilation of the initial dislocations occurs during the SPS [49]. As a result, a high density of dislocations can still be observed around the grain boundaries and oxide inclusions without plastic deformation, as shown in a bright-field image of the Al 0.5 (Fig. 8). Due to the high and large G of the bulk alloys, large contributions of dislocation strengthening were identified: the values of dis for the alloys were 720 (Al 0 ), 579 (Al 0.5 ), and 360 MPa (Al 1.0 ). This increase in dislocation strengthening effect with decreasing Al content may be due to the large accumulation of initial after the milling.

div.p: Concerning strengthening by oxide inclusions, the Orowan strengthening mechanism provides a better explanation than a dislocation shearing mechanism, due to the incoherence of the BCC matrices and relatively large size of the inclusions [50,51].

div.p: Traditional models for ss are based on dilute solution alloys, particularly for binary systems [54,55]. For HEAs, however, the conventional concepts of 'solute' and 'solvent' are not applicable due to the similar atomic concentrations of the alloying elements. Table 4 summarizes the G, density, total misfit effect ( i ε 2 i c i 2/3 ), ss , and phases of typical RHEAs. The total misfit and ss were calculated based on Wang's model discussed above. It is obvious that the AlxCrNbVMo RHEAs exhibited excellent combinations of G and total misfit effect, resulting in large ss . If the total misfit effect is much higher than that of AlxCrNbVMo RHEAs (∼1.026), a brittle intermetallic phase forms rather than a stable solid solution phase, such as CrNbTiZr RHEA. To our knowledge, the AlxCrNbVMo RHEAs have the highest ss among the BCC RHEAs consisting of a single BCC phase with density below 8.0 g/cm 3 . In addition, the Al concentration seems to have no influence on the ss of the AlxCrNbVMo RHEAs. Even though the total misfit effect increases with the addition of Al, the reduction in G results in a similar solid solution strengthening effect in AlxCrNbVMo RHEAs.

Based on the discussion above, the contributions of each strengthening mechanism to the yield strength of the Al 0 , Al 0.5 , and Al 1.0 RHEAs are summarized in Fig. 9 (the experimentally determined yield strengths of the alloys are marked by red circles) and Table 5. It can be seen that, for the quadratic model, the predicted values are in good agreement with the experimental values, with a small deviation (< 7%). This deviation may be attributable to several factors. First, the Poisson ratio was taken as that of pure Nb, resulting in a small discrepancy in G of the alloys, and consequently in ss , or and dis . Furthermore, the K HP used to calculate gb was taken from the Al 0.1 CrNbVMo alloy, in spite of the difference in alloy composition. Failure to take account of the effect of friction stress may also contribute to the deviation. Nonetheless, the experimental and predicted yield strengths of the three alloys match well. It is apparent that solid solution strengthening accounts for more than 50 % of the strengthening in the PM-processed AlxCrN-bVMo RHEAs, which is attributable to good combinations of the total misfit effect and G of the matrix. Owing to the refined grain size induced during high-energy ball milling and SPS, the grain boundary strengthening additionally improved the mechanical properties of the PM-processed RHEAs compared to other cast RHEAs. Due to the high G and of the PM-processed AlxCrNbVMo RHEAs, a large contribution of dislocation strengthening to the excellent mechanical properties of the alloys was also identified.

According to the literature [58], yield strength of single BCC RHEAs drops rapidly at temperature (T) over 0.6T m (T m : melting temperature of the alloy) due to the dominance of the diffusioncontrolled dislocation climb/glide than the diffusionless dislocation glide. At 1000 • C, the values of T/T m for Al 0 , Al 0.5 and Al 1.0 each alloy were, 0.50, 0.53 and 0.56, respectively, which represents that the reduction of the yield strength of the alloys will not be large. Thus, the superior strength of the alloys compared to the other RHEAs would be maintained at 1000 • C, resulting in the outstanding high temperature strength of the alloys. Orowan strengthening by oxide inclusions also contributes to the strength of the alloys at 1000 • C. Furthermore, inter-granular fracture was not observed after the compressive test at 1000 • C as shown in the fracture morphology of the Al 0 and Al 0.5 (Fig. S3). It may represent that the grain boundary strengthening contributes to the high-temperature strength of the alloys in the same manner at room temperature. To clarify this issue, we will investigate the deformation behaviors of the alloys at a high temperature as future work.

div.head: Conclusions
div.p: Lightweight RHEAs of AlxCrNbVMo (x = 0, 0.5, and 1.0) exhibiting a single BCC phase were fabricated successfully via PM. The microstructures of the bulk alloys were homogeneous, without chemical segregation, grain coarsening or micropores. A small amount of oxide inclusions was uniformly formed by in-situ reaction during the PM procedures. The alloys exhibited superior yield strength and specific yield strength compared to cast RHEAs at 25 and 1000 • C. Particularly, the Al 0 alloy exhibited an outstanding yield strength of 1513 MPa at 1000 • C. Furthermore, Al 0 showed 27 % and 87 % enhancement in its specific yield strength at 25 and 1000 • C, respectively, compared to that of AlMo 0.5 NbTa 0.5 TiZr HEA, which exhibited the best specific yield strength among the cast RHEAs. The quantitative analysis of the strengthening mechanisms revealed that solid solution strengthening was the predominant contributor, accounting for over 50 % of strengthening in the PMprocessed AlxCrNbVMo RHEAs. The large size and modulus misfit effects, and a high matrix modulus are attributable to a higher solid solution strengthening than that of typical BCC RHEAs. Advantages were obtained by high-energy ball milling and SPS, i.e., a relatively large and refined grain structures on the sub-micron scale, which made large contributions to strength due to grain boundary and dislocation strengthening effects in the PM-processed AlxCrNbVMo RHEAs.
